UNDIAGNOSED FATAL ILLNESS, CANINE - USA (NEW MEXICO): REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 23 Sep 2106
Source: KOB.com [edited]
http://www.kob.com/albuquerque-news/vets-puzzled-by-dozens-of-dog-deaths-in-albuquerque/4271726/


Pet owners are growing worried about a sudden illness that caused the deaths of 2 dogs and clinical signs in a 3rd that is recovering.

After those deaths, one woman put together an online survey, and after dozens of submissions from other residents, they think the illness could be more widespread. The problem is local vets have no idea what's causing it.

Chris Sturtz, a dog owner in Paradise Hills, has a 6-year-old dog named Roxxi. She was healthy and happy, and then all of a sudden, Sturtz took her to the vet and found a serious problem.

"I decided to go get liver enzymes tested and some blood work done, and my vet was stunned when they came back with elevated enzymes," Sturtz said.

It was a sign her neighbor, Kasia Zaryczny, told her was also discovered in her dog Luka, along with other signs like diarrhea and lack of appetite.

Much like Roxxi, Zaryczny said it happened out of nowhere; the only difference was that after 3 days, Luka had to be put down.

"My dog was perfectly fine, jumping, just a happy-go-lucky dog, then all of a sudden, she just got really sick," Zaryczny said.

It's the same story shared by another neighbor whose dog also died. Local veterinarians said they don't know what's causing it.

"We need to have the lab look at tissues and see, does it look like it's a bacterial infection? Does it look like a viral infection? Does it look like it's a toxic problem? We need more information to figure out exactly what's going on," Dr. George Abernathy said.

He said many of the clinical signs are too broad to attribute to one specific illness. Solving the mystery means doing more tests on dogs that do not survive.

"This is emergent; get your dog tested if your dog is sick; now that you know this is going on, get a necropsy," Sturtz said. "If Roxxi died, I would get a necropsy; she won't have died for nothing. Get your dog tested."

One crowd-sourcing survey found as many as 50 families reporting animal deaths with similar symptoms.

Abernathy said because the other 50 pets were not tested by him he can't say for sure that all the animals had the same illness. However, he encourages residents to monitor any illness your pet may have.

Local residents encourage other animal owners to participate in the survey that can be found in the Nextdoor App.

Albuquerque Animal Welfare officials said they are aware of the problem but have not received an uptick in calls for dead dogs. However, they said it is something they will continue to monitor.

[Byline: Brittany Costello]

