Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Aside from sick or dying dogs with elevated liver enzymes, anorexia (not eating) and diarrhea, there is not much else to go on.

This article does not mention any vomiting. Often with elevated liver enzymes, there is vomiting. This article does not mention any use of ultrasound to look at the abdomen for abscess or for fluid in the abdomen or other abnormalities or growths.

Necropsies of dogs that die are critical. The lesions in the tissues, especially the liver, may reveal whether it is a known toxin or a new and emerging toxin or other illness.

Liver disease was diagnosed a few times earlier and was in those previous years linked to aflatoxin in dog food. In both cases, it was an accidental contamination because of the way aflatoxin grows.

Aflatoxin, a naturally occurring chemical that comes from a fungus sometimes found on corn and other crops, can cause severe liver damage. Aflatoxin poisoning can cause sluggishness, a lack of appetite and in severe cases severe vomiting, fever and jaundice.

The growth aflatoxin is not uniform in a batch of grain. Dogs can and do recover from aflatoxin intoxication, however, an accurate diagnosis is required as well as testing of the food.

Levels of aflatoxin in dog food in the USA should be less than 20 parts per billion (ppb). Low levels of aflatoxin (21-250 or 300 ppm) will not cause visible signs of illness until the dog has consumed the contaminated food for 60-90 days. This situation is a chronic intoxication that has an acute presentation.

In other words, the dogs have been eating it for the 60-90 days but only suddenly become ill.

Although aflatoxin has been associated with cancer in people, it does not cause cancer in dogs. Dogs do not live long enough to develop any kind of cancer that may be associated with aflatoxin.

There is no indication as of this writing whether this illness is linked to any aflatoxin or dog food. However, thorough clinical records are needed, including blood work involving liver enzymes and GGT (gamma glutamyl transferase) as well histopathology on any animal succumbing to this mysterious illness.

We hope there are no other ill or deceased animals, but this bears watching at all levels of the veterinary world. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4514846,233.]
